{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11834"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.24,0.07,0.24,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55305"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4435"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43878"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55305"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department after vomiting a large quantity of blood. He was picked up from a house where there had been heavy drinking. The patient does not respond to questions, will not open his eyes, but does respond to painful stimuli. The ambulance officers inserted an intravenous cannula in the dorsum of his hand and started a saline infusion. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears critically unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 70/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. While being examined, the patient has a further episode of haematemesis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tilt the head of the trolley down","Insert a wider bore intravenous catheter","Administer 1 L isotonic saline over two hours","Transfuse one unit of group O negative blood","Perform endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with massive upper gastrointestinal bleeding, likely due to a complication of alcohol use such as a Mallory-Weiss tear or variceal bleeding. He is critically ill with signs of hypovolaemic shock and altered mental status. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform endotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndotracheal intubation is crucial in this scenario for several reasons: \u003Cbr /\u003E1. The patient has a depressed level of consciousness (not opening eyes, only responding to pain). \u003Cbr /\u003E2. There is an ongoing risk of aspiration due to recurrent haematemesis. \u003Cbr /\u003E3. The patient\u0027s airway needs protection to facilitate further resuscitation efforts safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETilting the head of the trolley down\u003C/strong\u003E might help reduce the risk of aspiration temporarily, but it does not adequately protect the airway in a patient with such a depressed level of consciousness and ongoing bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserting a wider bore intravenous catheter\u003C/strong\u003E is important for fluid resuscitation, but airway protection takes precedence in the ABCDE approach (Airway, Breathing, Circulation, Disability, Exposure).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering 1 L isotonic saline over two hours\u003C/strong\u003E is too slow for this critically ill patient. After airway protection, more rapid fluid resuscitation will be needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusing one unit of group O negative blood\u003C/strong\u003E will be necessary, but again, airway protection is the priority before initiating blood transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter intubation, the next steps would include establishing large-bore IV access, initiating rapid fluid resuscitation and blood transfusion, and arranging for urgent endoscopy. The underlying cause of the bleeding (e.g., varices, ulcer, Mallory-Weiss tear) will need to be identified and treated. Coagulation studies should be checked, and correction of any coagulopathy may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ABCDE approach should be prioritised in an acutely unwell, deteriorating patient.","Endotracheal intubation is indicated in patients with impaired consciousness and risk of aspiration.","Patients with massive upper gastrointestinal bleeding require immediate airway protection and resuscitation."],"references":["Upchurch BR. Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (UGIB)\u00a0Treatment \u0026 Management. https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/187857-treatment (accessed 25.2.20)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T14:57:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T14:59:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4435"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55305"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"descr